You just got engaged and now it’s full steam ahead with wedding planning. After much research, you booked your dream wedding photographer. Now it’s time for your engagement photos. You’ve nailed down the location and wardrobe, now all that’s left is the shoot itself. So let’s talk about poses for engagement photos. With attention to detail and a little preparation, you and your fiance will be able be present, enjoy your session and feel completely natural and comfortable in front of the camera.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
When it comes to posing, there are a few things to keep in mind: Body angles and stance. Posture and gaze. Movement and interaction.  For a more detailed explanation, click on over to the blog: https://tiffanyjphoto.com/blog/poses-for-engagement-photos/

Remember to take little moments throughout your wedding day to soak it all in.  This day is the culmination of all of your dreams and planning.  And finally, after all of the anticipation, your wedding day is finally here.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
From your first look to your reception reveal, be present.  The day will start out feeling incredibly surreal and then it will be over quicker than you could have imagined, so be sure to savor this experience.

I’m a big fan of first looks for many reasons … we can chat about all of those reasons later. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
But todays reason is that it allows you to enjoy cocktail hour with your guests.  There’s something so fun and meaningful about keeping the celebration going by exiting your ceremony + sharing a toast with your guests.

Movement and interaction are two of my favorite elements to focus on during engagement sessions. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It’s time to let loose and have some fun. Your engagement photography session should be enjoyable and memorable rather than dreaded and painful. This is a moment for you and your fiance to celebrate your engagement. So don’t be afraid to move, to dance, to sweep her off her feet and spin her around … to run off into the sunset. This is a celebration of your relationship. So smile at each other, snuggle into one another, kiss her cheek, give each other a bear hug, whisper in her ear … I think you get the point. But most of all, have fun with it … I guarantee you the candid,playful, candid, interactive shots will likely be your most cherished images.

Did you know that I include a complimentary engagement session in almost all of my wedding collections? 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

Not only does it give you an opportunity to test your hair + makeup to see how it will photograph, but it also provides you + your fiance time to feel comfortable in front of my lens by getting to know me + my shooting style.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I'll also give you some tips and tricks so you can become familiar with my posing techniques.  This way, come your wedding day, you know what to expect + will be able to flow through poses quickly + naturally.  This will help alleviate some of your stress + will enable us to work efficiently with limited time.

To dip, or not to dip, that is the question.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
If I'm being honest, I'm not a huge fan of the dramatic dip.  I know a lot of people love it, but hear me out.  In my humble opinion a dip feel forced.  I could be wrong, but it's rare that I see couples actually dip in everyday life.  But because we've been programmed to believe that a dip is the ultimate romantic pose, everyone now feels obligated to dip.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Often times these dips don't feel authentic, but rather end up looking forced, awkward and both the bride and groom end up looking extremely uncomfortable ... the bride fearing she's about to be dropped and the groom worrying that he's about to drop his new wife on their wedding day.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Instead, I'm a huge fan of a slight arch of the back as the groom pulls his bride in close and romantically leans in for a kiss.  Similar concept but much better results all around.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

I often get asked when a couple should schedule their engagement photos.  My answer always varies slightly depending on each couple, and here's why:

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
If you won't be using your engagement images on your save the dates, you have a bit more flexibility regarding timing.  If this I the case, I would recommend planning your session around the time of year and the scene you're envisioning. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This gorgeous green field we shot at for @gracechappelballa and @balladavid engagement session wouldn't have looked even remotely the same had we shot in the middle of summer when all of the tall grass was dried out.  Timing is everything when it comes to outdoor locations!

Choosing your wedding venue isn't just about ticking boxes! It's about finding the place that will showcase your love story in the most authentic way.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
A few things to consider are:
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
1.  The Vibe.  Do you prefer the intimate feel of a private estate?  The grand, sweeping views of a lakeside ceremony? Or the architectural elegance of an indoor venue?
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
2. Indoor vs. Outdoor: Embrace the open air or build cozy intimacy? Consider seasons, guest sizes, and backup plans! 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
3. Photos: (Clearly high on the priority list for me) Think beyond the ceremony! Where will you steal a kiss, laugh with bridesmaids, or capture that epic group shot? Pay attention to what types of images you're drawn to and evaluate if your potential venue can provide that.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
4.  Accessibility. (Another huge priority for me). If you have any guests with mobility impairments, assess the functionality of your venue and think through the impact an inaccessible venue will have on your guest's experience.  Pro tip: just because there's a random ramp near some hidden back entrance doesn't mean your venue is accessible.  Remember to make sure that there is an accessible bathroom, step-free entrances, etc.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Bonus tip: Tag your location and use relevant local hashtags to connect with amazing venues and vendors in your area!

YES please!!

6. Drop-Waist Silhouettes. Paired nicely with the rise of exposed corsetry, this silhouette feels modern and allows form to be highlighted in a beautiful way.
